arch:property.oc:show_val: Collapse in the south of the hypocaust room
1.70 m north south -by- 4.50 m east west.

Locus 22 consists of the collapse in the south part of the hypocaust room. The soil is a fine, loose silt with a Munsell color of 7.5 YR 5/4 (brown). There were many stones, of a whole range of sizes from ashlars to small stone fragments. A significant amount of pottery was also found in this locus. This layer of collapse was exposed at the beginning of the expansion of the trench to the south, and can be equated to Locus 4 in the north of the room. The locus was full of architectural fragments, primarily ashlars and capital fragments. Part of the main collapse of the bath complex, Locus 22 is assigned to Stage 7.

Phase XI: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.

Phase XIV: Modern period marked by Bedouin activity and the accumulation of recent debris. Nazzal's dump is dug between the collapsed Porch columns on the temple Forecourt. A German survey between the temple stylobate and Forecourt results in the disturbance of these deposits.
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue. Upper levels of fluvial wash are deposited. Rooms A and B are abandoned.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
